# Git Workflow Rules

## Commit Messages
- Conventional commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`, `test:`, `chore:`, `perf:`, `build:`, `ci:`.
- Scope in parentheses when useful: `fix(auth): correct token refresh`.
- Present tense, imperative mood: "add feature", not "added feature".
- Reference the ticket when applicable, using this project's ticket prefix (`{{TRACKER_KEY}}`):
  `fix(auth): correct token refresh ({{TRACKER_KEY}}-123)`.

## The unit of work
- **1 ticket = 1 branch = 1 PR.** Each task gets its own branch off the integration branch
  and lands as a single reviewable pull request.
- Branch names are descriptive and tied to the ticket: `feat/{{TRACKER_KEY}}-123-short-description`,
  `fix/{{TRACKER_KEY}}-124-short-description`.

## What to Commit
- Working code only — every commit should leave the project in a runnable state.
- One logical change per commit — don't mix a feature with an unrelated refactor.
- Keep tightly-coupled changes (e.g. an interface and its callers) in the same commit.

## What NOT to Commit
- `.env` files or anything containing secrets, tokens, or credentials.
- Build artifacts and dependency directories (e.g. `node_modules/`, `__pycache__/`, `dist/`, `build/`).
- Editor/IDE-local and OS files (`.vscode/`, `.idea/`, `.DS_Store`, `Thumbs.db`).
- Generated handoff state that is meant to be local: `docs/context_snapshot.md`.
- Large binaries that don't belong in version control.

## Never
- Force-push (`git push --force`) to a shared branch.
- `git reset --hard`, `git clean -f`, or any history-rewriting/destructive command without explicit approval.
- Commit directly to the protected/default branch when review is expected.
- Leave merge conflicts unresolved or commit conflict markers.
